## Subsetting script (reproducibility)

`products.json` and `queries.csv` were generated by the script below. Re-running
the script against the upstream parquets reproduces the exact files (modulo
upstream dataset updates — the snapshot used was downloaded 2026-05-12 from
`https://github.com/amazon-science/esci-data/raw/main/shopping_queries_dataset/`).

Selection criteria:
- Locale: `us` (English).
- Split: `train` (test rows excluded so MVP1 evaluation can adopt the test split later).
- `small_version=1` (Task 1 reduced set — manually curated, smaller, cleaner).
- Pick 50 queries with all 4 of E/S/C/I labels and depth ≥ 5; sort by depth desc,
  then `query_id` ascending for determinism.
- Collect every product referenced by those queries; cap at the first 1,000
  product_ids alphabetically (deterministic).
- Drop products with empty `product_title`.
- Truncate per-product fields so the JSON file stays under the 500 KB pre-commit
  large-file threshold while preserving enough text for an LLM judge to evaluate
  relevance: `title` ≤ 140 chars, `description` ≤ 160 chars, ≤ 3 bullet points
  each ≤ 80 chars (truncated at word boundaries with a trailing `...`).
- Encode JSON compactly (`separators=(",", ":")`) — saves ~30% file size; the
  smoke test + `seed_es.py` parse with `json.loads()` either way.
- Apply the coverage filter: only retain queries whose final product set still
  has ≥ 5 judged products in the capped subset (yields 48 queries from the 50
  candidates after the 1,000-product cap drops 2 thin queries).

```python
"""ESCI subsetting script — produces samples/products.json + samples/queries.csv.
Source: Amazon ESCI shopping queries dataset (CC-BY-4.0).
       https://github.com/amazon-science/esci-data
"""

from __future__ import annotations

import csv
import json
import re
from pathlib import Path

import pandas as pd
import pyarrow.parquet as pq

SRC = Path("/tmp/esci-curate")  # download examples.parquet + products.parquet here first
OUT_PRODUCTS = Path("samples/products.json")
OUT_QUERIES = Path("samples/queries.csv")

TARGET_QUERIES = 50
TARGET_PRODUCTS = 1000

TITLE_MAX, DESC_MAX, BULLET_COUNT, BULLET_MAX = 140, 160, 3, 80

examples = pq.read_table(SRC / "examples.parquet").to_pandas()
filtered = examples[
    (examples["product_locale"] == "us")
    & (examples["split"] == "train")
    & (examples["small_version"] == 1)
].dropna(subset=["product_id", "esci_label", "query_id", "query"])

per_query = (
    filtered.groupby(["query_id", "query"])
    .agg(label_count=("esci_label", "nunique"), depth=("product_id", "nunique"))
    .reset_index()
)
strict = per_query[(per_query["label_count"] == 4) & (per_query["depth"] >= 5)]
chosen = strict.sort_values(["depth", "query_id"], ascending=[False, True]).head(TARGET_QUERIES)

referenced = filtered[filtered["query_id"].isin(chosen["query_id"])]
ids = sorted(set(referenced["product_id"]))[:TARGET_PRODUCTS]

products = pq.read_table(
    SRC / "products.parquet",
    columns=["product_id", "product_title", "product_description",
             "product_bullet_point", "product_brand", "product_color", "product_locale"],
).to_pandas()
picked = products[(products["product_locale"] == "us") & (products["product_id"].isin(ids))]


def clean(t):  # strip HTML, collapse whitespace
    if t is None:
        return ""
    s = re.sub(r"<[^>]+>", " ", str(t))
    return re.sub(r"\s+", " ", s).strip()


def trunc(s, n):
    if len(s) <= n:
        return s
    return s[:n].rsplit(" ", 1)[0] + "..."


rows = []
for _, r in picked.iterrows():
    title = clean(r["product_title"])
    if not title:
        continue
    bullets = []
    if r["product_bullet_point"] is not None:
        for b in re.split(r"[\r\n]+", str(r["product_bullet_point"])):
            b = clean(b)
            if b:
                bullets.append(trunc(b, BULLET_MAX))
            if len(bullets) >= BULLET_COUNT:
                break
    rows.append({
        "id": str(r["product_id"]),
        "title": trunc(title, TITLE_MAX),
        "description": trunc(clean(r["product_description"]), DESC_MAX),
        "brand": clean(r["product_brand"]),
        "color": clean(r["product_color"]),
        "bullet_points": bullets,
    })

rows.sort(key=lambda x: x["id"])
# Compact JSON (no whitespace) keeps the file under the 500KB pre-commit limit.
OUT_PRODUCTS.write_text(json.dumps(rows, ensure_ascii=False, separators=(",", ":")))

final_ids = {r["id"] for r in rows}
final_pairs = filtered[filtered["query_id"].isin(chosen["query_id"]) & filtered["product_id"].isin(final_ids)]
covered = set(final_pairs.groupby("query_id").size().pipe(lambda s: s[s >= 5]).index)
final = chosen[chosen["query_id"].isin(covered)].head(TARGET_QUERIES)

with OUT_QUERIES.open("w", newline="") as fh:
    w = csv.writer(fh)
    w.writerow(["query_id", "query_text"])
    for _, r in final.iterrows():
        w.writerow([str(r["query_id"]), str(r["query"])])
```

## Notes

- The 1,000-product cap is intentional. Larger subsets push smoke-test runtime
  (single 10-trial study against 5 queries with LLM-generated judgments) above
  the 5-minute budget the smoke gate enforces.
- The 48-query CSV is intentionally short of the 50-query target for the same
  reason: dropping the queries that lost ≥5-product coverage after the product
  cap keeps the dataset internally consistent (every query has enough judged
  documents in the seeded index for `ndcg@10` to be informative).
- `products.bullet_points` is split on newlines; the upstream HTML in the
  ESCI parquet is stripped.
- No personally identifying information ships in this directory. ESCI is a
  product-catalog dataset (no user names, accounts, or session-level data).
